# intentc -- A Compiler of Intent

intentc is a build system that reads written, interdepedendent intents and generates working code using AI Agents. 

Developers author spec incrementally define files describing *what* they want, and intentc orchestrates AI agents to produce *how* as a reproducible artifact. 

## Philosophy

The goal of this project is to create a build system that can reproducibly, and incrementally, generate code and other artifacts from Intent. The user is responsible for clearly defining what it is they want
with sufficient detail that it can be handed off to an agent. As the project progresses in time, new intents are added, and old intents are updated, each triggering a new build that updates the code base. If the project is 
well defined, all the code should be able to be deleted and a sufficiently "similar" code base can be regenerated from purely the intent files. If this property is true then the code is now the intent files and the developers
have successfully raised the level of abstraction. 

This project supports the above by providing the tooling, tracking, and extensibility needed to achieve this in a disciplined manner. Rather than prompting coding agents adhoc and relying on convention, this project enforces
reporducibility with its file layout, emphasis on validation, ease of generation and reproducible builds, as well as other tooling to encourage defining all that is needed in the intent files

- **Specs are the source of truth.** Intent files (.ic) and validation files (.icv) are human-authored, version-controlled documents that capture product intent independently of implementation.
- **Validation constrains generation.** Validations are co-authored with intents and guide the agent toward correct output. Tighter constraints produce more reproducible results.
- **Agents are pluggable and customizable** Any CLI tool that accepts prompts can be a code generation agent. The agent interface is minimal and extensible, future proofing and specializing the build system to the user needs
- **Managed State**: Specs and generated files are managed with version control, with a clear separated history of intent changes versus generated changes
- **Observable**: Builds are logged and have clear steps and summaries from the agents to allow a developer to understand what happened in the layer below. Updating intents requires an understanding of the compilation step and modifying to get the desired outcome
- **Isolated**: The build is isolated from the rest of the system so that it can only access the current generated artifacts, and the relevant intents without any future intents or alternative implementations. 

## Project Structure

An intentc project has the following structure defined below. The specific file formats are defined in as part of the intent files

```
project-root/
  .intentc/
    config.yaml            # Default runtime config (agent profiles, build system prompts, output directory) -- can be overridden
    state/                 # Build state tracking (gitignored)
      {output-dir}/        # State is tracked by output directory and independent of other output directories
        build-log.jsond    # The build log is an append only log of all the steps taken for the project. 
  intent/
    project.ic             # What this project is and why
    implementation.ic      # How it's built (language, libs, conventions, infrastructure)
    assertions/
      *.icv                # A project level assertion that is not tied to any particular feature. 
    {module}/              # Can be arbitrarily nested
       {feature}/
        *.ic               # Feature intent(s) -- can be dependent on other feature intents by referencing {module / feature}
        *.icv              # Feature validations -- different types and different conventions. Think of them as tests or validation to be run after the feature is completed and iterated on until they pass. 
        *.*                # Any supporitng materials referenced in the intent files via relative local paths (can reference files elsewhere)
  {output-dir}/            # Generated code -- default is `src` and can be modified
```

## Core Workflows

The core workflows of the project are defined below with the intended steps. This is not to rule out other workflows, but meant as an anchoring guide for the project. 

### Initialize a Project

As a user I come to a new folder to start a project, I run `intentc init` and my project structure is generated such that I can start defining my project. I focus a lot on the core
project.ic and accompanying implementation.ic, as well as initial features. I then build iteratively from there

### Iteratively add new feature, with refinement

As a user, With an existing project i create a new feature with `intentc add feature/name` as a bite-sized improvement in functionality. I define what is needed in the .ic and .icv files and run build with `intentc build feature/name`. 
The .icv are automatic validations that are iterated on by the agent until they pass. Then there is manual review, where I look at the code diffs, the runtime, or any other validation mechanism i have to see if the intended effect occured. 
If not I clean out the build with `intentc clean feature/name` and tweak what I need to then run build again, until the outcome  is what I am looking for. 

### "Refactor" an existing features

As a user, sometimes down the line in a project I realize i made a poor assumption in some feature that's upstream of where the lead nodes are. I go back and tweak the assumptions there and then run `intentc build feature/name`. This prunes all existing
downstream features and then regenerates the current feature. I iterate here to my liking then run `intentc build` which builds the full project to the leaf nodes. Build history is preserved in the version control system in case I feel taht i have gone off the rails
I can roll back to the specific version prior to my refactoring, similar to git. 

### Validate the project

As a user I want to regularly test my project is working as intended. I can run `intentc validate` which looks up all the .icv files and validates each one sequentially, similar to a test suite. Validating that the project works as intended. These .icv files
need not be confined to a particular feature and can be project or system level tests as well. A report is generated with status of passing and not passing that I can inspect. 

### Rebuild the project 

As a user, sometimes new agents, new languages, new frameworks come along that make me want to rebuild the project from scatch to a new target. Here I can run `intentc build -o new-output` after updating implementation.ic, config.yaml, 
or other files. This new output folder is built under the new paradigm. I can then COMPARE the new built target to the existing built project with `intentc` utilities to validate that they work via `intentc compare src new-output` which generates
a report. This comparison is a difficult one and will not catch everything, but combined with the .icv files I can understand the differences and similarities.

